  findings:
    - "Intent clarity HIGH treats wrap-an-existing-installer as a single unambiguous outcome, but the source's load-bearing line `curl -fsSL https://cortex.sh/install | sh` depends on ticket 118's installer endpoint, which the source asserts without evidence."
    - "Intent clarity HIGH does not address what brew owns when the curl script does the install — there is no binary in the formula prefix and `brew uninstall` would not undo the curl install, which the source glosses as a single unambiguous outcome."
    - "Scope boundedness HIGH cites enumerated lists, but the in-scope upgrade path (`brew upgrade` re-runs the curl script) is structurally the same hazard the source's own Research section flags (post_install runs on every brew upgrade), without resolving the contradiction."
    - "Requirements alignment HIGH invokes DR-8's proposed project.md update while conceding the update has not landed; until it lands, the ticket is in direct textual conflict with the current `Published packages or reusable modules for others` Out-of-Scope clause."
    - "Complexity simple assumes a mechanical pattern the source never demonstrates and the source itself notes 'no surveyed project ships primarily via Homebrew'; multiple judgment calls (tap repo owner, pin vs latest, brew audit style, version string under uv tool install) are not engaged."
    - "Criticality medium reasons about install-time recoverability but does not engage with the source's own flagged upgrade-time hazard — silent overwrite of user customizations on every brew upgrade is not recoverable via tap update."
